comment.body: Streamlined my own code a bit by defining `vec(A::Matrix, i::Integer) = vec(A[i,:])` so I can do `foo(vec(A, i))` instead of `foo(vec(A[i,:]))`

issue.body:
I know the "1xN matrices vs. vectors" is a debatable issue (and read a few other issue comment threads which have mentioned it). However, in my work lately I found it really annoying that a one-dimensional slice of a matrix is not a Vector.

I have some functions (such as coordinate transformations) which I first wrote to take a Vector{Float64}. When I'm dealing with a large number of vectors, for me the natural way of storing the data is in a Matrix{Float64}. Unfortunately, this is the case:

```
julia> function foo(x::Vector)
         x # Actual stuff would go here
       end

julia> A = randn(5,3)
5x3 Float64 Array:
 -0.875508  -0.415628  -0.0329144
  0.536076   0.658193   1.53601  
  0.143337  -0.145942  -0.39764  
  0.159293  -0.778494   0.221653 
 -0.558092   0.833631  -1.47995  

julia> v = A[1,:]
1x3 Float64 Array:
 -0.875508  -0.415628  -0.0329144

julia> foo(v)
no method foo(Array{Float64,2},)
 in method_missing at base.jl:60
```

What would be the best way to work around this? I wouldn't want to do `v = reshape(A[i,:], 3)` every timeâ€¦ The other obvious alternative I can think of is to write my functions to take an Array instead of a Vector, but that then renders Vector a bit useless.

I suppose treating these slices as vectors would have its own problems, but I would think storing a bunch of vectors as a matrix is a very common thing to do.
issue.title: Matrix slices vs. Vectors

comment.body: What user does cap log in as? Is it the same user you're ssh'ing in with?

issue.body:
When I run `cap deploy` it will return an error that whenever command is not found. In my deploy file I have
```ruby
require 'whenever/capistrano'
task :update_crontab, :roles => :db do
  run "cd #{release_path} && bundle exec whenever --update-crontab reminder"
end
```
However if I ssh in the server and run `bundle exec whenever --update-crontab reminder` it will return
```ruby
0 3 * * * /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /app/myapp/releases/20120614174754 && script/rails runner -e production '\''MyModel.reminder'\'''
```

But I'm still not receiving any reminder emails. It works if I run it locally but not when I deploy it to linode.
issue.title: whenever not working on linode
